href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
href="jms-00K7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00K7">partial function</fr:link> <fr:tex>f \colon  A \mathbin { \rightharpoonup }  B</fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>total</fr:strong></fr:em> whenever its <fr:link
href="jms-00KB.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KB">domain of definition</fr:link> coincides with its domain (source), i.e. we have <fr:tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}} { \downarrow }</fr:tex> for all <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex>. In this case, we will write <fr:tex>f \colon  A \to  B</fr:tex> and refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>function</fr:strong></fr:em> or a <fr:em><fr:strong>map</fr:strong></fr:em>. Sometimes, we redundantly refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>total function</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p><fr:p>Just as we write <fr:tex>\mathrm {Rel} { \mathopen {} \left ( A,B \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \mathbin { \rightharpoonup }  B \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>for the sets of <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relations</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="jms-00K7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00K7">partial functions</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> respectively, we shall write <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \to  B \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> for the set of functions from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>B</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree
